From: marcus@ursula.ee.pdx.edu (Marcus Daniels)
Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
Subject: Re: Hurd status and call for volunteers
Date: 5 Nov 1993 04:34:20 -0800

becker@super.org (Donald J. Becker) writes:

>In article <2b7jsk$eu7@ursula.ee.pdx.edu>,
>Marcus Daniels <marcus@ursula.ee.pdx.edu> wrote:
>>Read mib's paper of the Hurd architecture before making inappropriate
>>comparisions.

>If you are talking about the early Hurd architecture paper, yes I read it.

>_YEARS_ ago.

I'm probably just uninformed, but the first I ever saw that paper was
Feb. '93.  I can't imagine it is more than a year older than that.

Getting up to speed on kernel development apparently has been
difficult for the FSF, but I really doubt it had anything to do with
them working on it internally, except to the extent they didn't have
the resources to do so.

>The point here is that having people wait for neat new vaporware isn't nearly
>as useful as having people use and improve something that's really pretty much
>as useful as that neat new idea.  I'll repeat the oft-used example of the BSD
>shared library implementation: early-on the BSD supporters ridiculed the Linux
>single-version shared library implementation and proudly stated that BSD would
>have a far superior shared library implementation.  Later the Linux
>jump-table library was released.  The BSD people claimed that it was all a
>time-wasting mistake, and that Linux would be stuck with something inferior to
>BSD's _dynamic_ shared libraries (coming RSN).  Today Linux has
>dynamically-linked shared libraries.  The last I heard the BSD crowd was
>thinking of using the Linux implementation.

Talk about O.S. hairsplitting.... ;-)

You make a good point, though.  Getting something `out the door' can
be difficult when the product is imperfect.  Often momentum is more important 
than the product itself.  My impression was that the FSF (rms
especially) was actually pretty expedient in these matters.

>I think this is a close analog to the Hurd vs. Linux issue.  The GNU project
>made a mistake when it rejected Linux as an ugly step-sister.  (hmmm, gotta
>watch those mixed metaphors.)  I see a future where people say "GNU? I've
>think I've heard of that -- isn't it the name of the Linux license?"

At the risk of being divisive (more than you), I think perhaps some of
the `Linux people' are underestimating the extent we have benefitted from
the FSF's effort.  There is more to an O.S. than device drivers.

Sure, for single user systems, with kernel source code and/or loadable kernel
servers, the practical advantage of the Hurd device-driver is reduced
-- but there are lots of other Mach'ism that Linux doesn't even
approximate:  multithreading, multiprocessing, distributed MMUs,
multiple O.S. personalities, external everything, etc..  More than
hacking have gone into Mach.  

Rather than trying to kludge up versions of the Hurd/Mach
functionality for Linux, it seems to me we'd all be better off
taking the information in all those device drivers and adapting them
to Hurd.

------------------------------

From: jjsf@gmv.es (Julio Sanchez)
Subject: Create your own Slackware Labels
Date: Fri, 5 Nov 1993 11:34:16 GMT


        - Did you download the slackware labels and could not find the 
          AVERY 5196 labels anywhere?

        - Do you have some different labels you would like to use?

        - Do you want labels for the TeX series too?

        - Do you want to define your own labels?

        - You tried to modify those labels and failed?

Well, if any of the above is true and you have TeX, dvips and a PostScript
printer, you might find the program below useful. It creates labels for
Slackware 1.1.0 and is flexible enough to serve as a template to create
labels on whatever paper you might have. To use this, you need the labels
for Slackware prepared by Alan M Buckwalter because you will have to extract
the logo from there. How to do it is explained below. The result is not
identical to his, though I have approximated it a lot.

Enjoy,

Julio


=============================   Cut here   ===========================
% This LaTeX program generates labels for Slackware diskettes. It is
% based on a design by Alan M Buckwalter (alan@qsss01.eq.gs.com),
% updated for A4 paper. You need the PostScript logo in his labels
% that you can get from ftp.cdrom.com. Get one of his label sets and
% extract the logo. Look for the lines starting with:
%
% %!PS-Adobe-2.0 EPSF-1.2
% %%Creator: FreeHand 3.1
% %%Title: Linux Logo
%
% You should find them around line 1733. Cut these lines up to those
% beginning with:
%
% %%Trailer
% end  % FreeHandDict
% end  % FHIODict
%
% And save everything in a file logo.ps. Running wc in my copy, I get:
%
%    548    1914   13566 logo.ps
%
% I give those numbers so you can check you did not take 2 or more
% copies of the logo with more code interspersed. A small difference
% should not matter.
%
% Then you process with TeX this file and send it to your printer with
% dvips -m (to force manual feed). The paper I use is REF. 1290 in the
% APLI catalog, that you might not find elsewhere. This paper has four
% rows of labels with three labels per row plus top and bottom margins
% of 12mm. It should be more or less clear how to change this file to
% other papers.
%
% WARNING: You don't want to mess with the percent signs at the end of
% the lines. You should not receive a single overfull or underfull box
% message. If you do, you have most likely broken something.

% These come with dvips
\documentstyle[epsf,rotate]{article}

% All TeX dvi drivers have the origin at (1in, 1in). We don't want
% that in this case, so we fix it.
\hoffset -1in
\voffset -1in

% We use the full A4 page.
\setlength{\textwidth}{210mm}
% This is overkill, but doesn't matter. We should subtract \headheight
% and \topmargin.
\setlength{\textheight}{297mm}

% Prevent TeX from messing our lines.
\setlength{\parindent}{0pt}

% You may want to tune this for your paper and your printer. Is the
% amount the label is moved downwards with respect to the nominal
% position. Your printer might be misadjusted.
\setlength{\topmargin}{1mm}

% No separation from header and body.
\setlength{\headsep}{0pt}
% The top unused strip.
\setlength{\headheight}{12mm}

% No margins
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{0pt}
\setlength{\evensidemargin}{0pt}

% Four fonts needed
\newfont{\una}{ptmr at 12pt} % Adobe Times Roman
\newfont{\dos}{pagk at 9 pt} % Adobe AvantGarde Book
\newfont{\tres}{pagk at 8pt}
\newfont{\cuatro}{pagk at 6pt}

% The height of your labels. Nominal is 67.7 but is too large for me.
% Even 67.6 is a bit too large.
\newlength{\LabelHeight}\setlength{\LabelHeight}{67.6mm}

% The width of your labels.
\newlength{\LabelWidth}\setlength{\LabelWidth}{70mm}

% Left and right margins in your labels. If you set them too low, your
% printer might clip your labels. The below value is for a LaserJet 4m.
\newlength{\LabelMargin}\setlength{\LabelMargin}{5mm}

\newcommand{\LineInBox}[1]{%
  \hbox to\LabelWidth{\hskip\LabelMargin #1\hskip\LabelMargin}}

\newcommand{\Label}[1]{\SpecialLabel{#1}{disk #1}}

\newcommand{\SpecialLabel}[2]{%
  \leavevmode
  \hbox to\LabelWidth{%
    \vbox to\LabelHeight{%
      \rotate[u]{%
        \hbox to \LabelWidth{%
          \vbox{%
            \LineInBox{\dos Linux\hfill \tres #2}%
            \vspace{3mm}
            \LineInBox{\cuatro Linux - 1.1.0 release\hfill
                   Copylefts and trademarks apply}%
            \vspace{-2mm}
            \LineInBox{\cuatro Slackware Release\hfill
                   Download from ftp.cdrom.com}%
          }%
        }%
      }%
      \LineInBox{\hfill\epsfbox{logo.ps}\hfill}%
      \LineInBox{\hskip 1cm \una Linux #1\hfill}%
      \vss
    }%
  }%
}

% \hss is included below because of rounding errors. If you use this
% for a different paper, you may want to delete it while you debug
% your new definition. I then get underfull boxes (four per page).
\newcommand{\Line}[1]{\hbox to \textwidth{#1\hss}}

\begin{document}
% Now our labels.
% This might not be obvious, but the % at the end of this line
% *is* required.
\Line{\SpecialLabel{Boot}{Boot Disk}\SpecialLabel{Rescue}{Rescue Disk}%
   \Label{a1}}
\Line{\Label{a2}\Label{a3}\Label{a4}}
\Line{\Label{a5}\Label{a6}\Label{a7}}
\Line{\Label{a8}\Label{a9}\Label{a10}}
%
\Line{\Label{a11}\Label{a12}\Label{a13}}
\Line{\Label{a14}\Label{e1}\Label{e2}}
\Line{\Label{e3}\Label{e4}\Label{e5}}
\Line{\Label{f1}\Label{oop1}\Label{y1}}
%
\Line{\Label{x1}\Label{x2}\Label{x3}}
\Line{\Label{x4}\Label{x5}\Label{xap1}}
\Line{\Label{xap2}\Label{xd1}\Label{xd2}}
\Line{\Label{xd3}\Label{xv1}\Label{xv2}}
%
\Line{\Label{iv1}\Label{iv2}\Label{tcl1}}
\Line{\Label{oi1}\Label{oi2}\Label{oi3}}
\Line{\SpecialLabel{Alpha Boot}{Alpha Boot Disk}\Label{q1}\Label{q2}}
\Line{\Label{t1}\Label{t2}\Label{t3}}
\end{document}


% Local Variables: 
% mode: latex
% TeX-master: t
% End: 






