From: hoenig@immd3.informatik.uni-erlangen.de (Joachim Hoenig)
Crossposted-To: comp.windows.x.i386unix
Subject: Re: ``Dynamic Cache Architecture''
Date: Fri, 5 Nov 1993 13:40:51 GMT

rmast@cs.vu.nl (Mast RN) writes:

>hoenig@immd3.informatik.uni-erlangen.de (Joachim Hoenig) writes:

>>Cheapy-yucky
>>motherboards like to omit the dirty-tag RAM ($5). This causes a cache
>>line to be always written back to (very slow) main memory before it is
>>loaded. Some motherboards do not even have the dirty-tag RAM socket

>How do you see whether a motherboard is equipped witch such a RAM or a socket?

Look for one or two empty sockets near the Cache RAM. If you don't find
any, you may look for places were the sockets might go. If you don't
find these tell-tale signs, your motherboard may or may not have the
dirty tag RAM.  Your board may have a write-through Cache and not need
dirty tags.  The only way to tell is with benchmark programs. There was
a DOS program called cachemes.exe published in the german c't'
magazine. I think I can post it next week together with some results.

Joachim

